You are assisting in the development of the Robo DeFi Advisor (RDA) DAO Treasury Management Module. Always follow the defined project architecture and MVP constraints. The project structure must remain organized into `core/`, `data/`, `agents/`, and `tests/` directories. Shared schemas and system primitives must live in `core/` (such as treasury_policy.py, mandate.py, audit.py, proposal_templates.py, protocol_registry.py). External data clients and API integrations must live only in the `data/` layer (such as defi_llama_client.py and protocol_clients). Business logic must live inside modular agents under `agents/` (discovery_agent, risk_agent, decision_agent, explanation_agent, treasury_agent). The treasury_agent acts only as the orchestration layer that runs the pipeline. Agents must never call external APIs directly; all data access must go through the data layer. The MVP scope is strictly limited to a Treasury Advisor and Governance Proposal Generator. The system must never implement autonomous fund movement, executor agents, wallet integrations, smart contract interactions, multisig integrations, circuit breakers, emergency withdrawals, monitoring agents, or any other execution capabilities. Those are Phase-2 or Phase-3 features and must not appear in MVP code. All treasury operations must be policy-driven and tied to a DAO mandate. The treasury flow must always load and validate a mandate, apply the TreasuryPolicy constraints, run discovery, risk filtering, decision ranking, generate explanations, produce a governance proposal draft, write an audit log, and return a recommendation output. If a mandate is missing, invalid, or expired, the pipeline must stop and return an error instead of continuing. The TreasuryPolicy schema is the single source of truth and all discovery, risk filtering, and decision logic must enforce its constraints including minimum APY, maximum APY, allowed protocols, allowed chains, minimum pool TVL, maximum allocation per pool, risk minimum score, and risk maximum level. Pool recommendations must be deterministic and explainable. The decision engine must rank pools using a reproducible scoring function such as a weighted combination of normalized APY, risk score, and TVL. The system must not rely on LLM-based decision making for ranking. Each recommended pool must include protocol, chain, APY, TVL, risk score, risk level, and a clear explanation of why it passed policy filters. The system must optionally support awareness of existing treasury positions when generating allocation suggestions so diversification limits can be respected. The treasury pipeline output must always include recommended pools, suggested allocation split, expected portfolio APY, a governance proposal draft in Markdown format compatible with Snapshot or Tally, and an audit log record. Governance proposal drafts must include title, allocation summary, protocol and pool details, expected APY, risk score, mandate ID, and approval reference. Every treasury run must generate an append-only audit log entry containing run_id, mandate_id, policy_snapshot, recommendation_output, and timestamp. Code generated for this project must follow Python best practices including PEP8 formatting, clear type hints, descriptive docstrings, and modular design. Avoid unnecessary dependencies and prefer standard libraries plus lightweight packages such as requests, pydantic, and pytest. Every module must include unit tests under the `tests/` directory. Tests should cover policy validation, mandate loading, risk filtering, and decision ranking logic. When implementing features, Cursor must work incrementally and implement only one module or feature at a time without rewriting unrelated parts of the codebase. Existing modules should not be refactored unless explicitly required. Large architectural changes must be proposed before implementation. Development should follow a disciplined workflow: implement a module, write tests, verify integration with the pipeline, and then proceed to the next component. The AI should prioritize deterministic, transparent, and secure behavior at all times, ensuring the system never performs any fund custody or transaction execution and always positions itself as a governance-aligned treasury recommendation engine.
